{"title_page": "COVID-19 pandemic in Boston", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Boston, United States}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=May 2020}}\n{{for|effects of the pandemic in the state|COVID-19 pandemic in Massachusetts}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = COVID-19 pandemic in Boston\n| image           = Empty Northeastern University campus, March 2020.jpg\n| caption         = An empty [[Northeastern University]], in Boston, after most of the students were required to leave\n| location        = [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| first_case      = [[South Boston]]<ref>{{cite web | title = Boston Man has Coronavirus, Mass. Health Officials Confirm | url=https://www.wbur.org/news/2020/02/01/coronavirus-boston-massachusetts | website=[[WBUR-FM]] | access-date=May 2, 2020}}</ref>\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| arrival_date    = February 1, 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=02|day1=1|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| confirmed_cases = 9,929 {{as of|2020|05|03|alt=as of May 3}}<ref name=\"Boston-Dashboard\">{{cite web | title = Boston COVID-19 Dashboard | url = https://dashboard.cityofboston.gov/t/Guest_Access_Enabled/views/COVID-19/Dashboard1?:showAppBanner=false&:display_count=n&:showVizHome=n&:origin=viz_share_link&:isGuestRedirectFromVizportal=y&:embed=y | website = Boston Public Health Commission | access-date = May 1, 2020}}</ref>\n| recovery_cases  = 2,309 {{as of|2020|05|03|alt=as of May 3}}<ref name=\"Boston-Dashboard\"/>\n| deaths          = 426 {{as of|2020|05|03|alt=as of May 3}}<ref name=\"Boston-Dashboard\"/>\n| active_cases    = 7,194 {{as of|2020|05|03|alt=as of May 3}}<ref name=\"Boston-Dashboard\"/>\n| hospitalized_cases  = 937 {{as of|2020|04|30|alt=as of April 30}}<ref group=\"note\" name=\"Boston-April30\">{{cite web | title=Boston COVID-19 Report April 30 | url=https://www.bphc.org/whatwedo/infectious-diseases/Documents/COVID19%20Boston%20Report_2020_Week18.pdf | website = Boston Public Health Commission | access-date = May 3, 2020}}</ref>\n| website         = https://www.boston.gov/news/coronavirus-disease-covid-19-boston\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n}}\nThe '''COVID-19 pandemic in Boston''' is part of an [[COVID-19 pandemic in Massachusetts|ongoing pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in the [[Massachusetts]] [[city]] of [[Boston]]. The first confirmed case was reported on February 1, 2020, and the number began to increase rapidly by March 9. The [[Governor of Massachusetts]], [[Charlie Baker]] declared a state of emergency on March 10. By March 21, over 100 people in Boston had tested positive for COVID-19. Most early cases were traceable to a company meeting held in late February by the [[biotechnology]] firm [[Biogen]] in Boston. {{As of|2020|05|03|df=US}}, there were 9,929 confirmed cases and 426 deaths due to COVID-19. {{As of|2020|04|29|alt=As of April 29}}, Boston had completed 27,824 tests, 32.1% of which came back positive.<ref name=\"Boston-Dashboard\"/><ref name=\"Boston-Data\">{{cite web | title = Boston COVID-19 Data | url=https://www.bphc.org/whatwedo/infectious-diseases/Infectious-Diseases-A-to-Z/covid-19/Pages/Boston-COVID-19-Data.aspx | website = Boston Public Health Commission | access-date = May 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n=== February ===\nThe first confirmed case of COVID-19 was reported by state officials on February 1. The individual, a male in his 20s, had recently returned from [[Wuhan]], [[China]] and began experiencing symptoms. He sought medical care but did not require hospitalization, and was therefore able to self-isolate and recover at home.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\">{{cite web | title = Boston Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Timeline | url=https://www.boston.gov/departments/public-health-commission/coronavirus-timeline | website = Boston Public Health Commission | access-date=May 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n175 executives of Biogen, a biotechnology company based in Cambridge, held a two-day leadership conference from February 26\u201328 at the Boston Marriott Long Wharf hotel.<ref name=\"Arsenault\">{{Cite news | last = Arsenault | first = Mark | url = https://www.bostonglobe.com/2020/03/11/nation/how-biogen-leadership-conference-boston-spread-coronavirus/ | title = How the Biogen leadership conference in Boston spread the coronavirus | date = March 10, 2020 | work = [[The Boston Globe]] | access-date = March 13, 2020 | last2 = Rosen | first2 = Andy | last3 = Krueger | first3 = Hanna | last4 = Lazar | first4 = Kay | last5 = Saltzman | first5 = Jonathan | last6 = Kowalczyk | first6 = Liz}}</ref> On February 29, a [[Biogen]] executive began to develop symptoms and sought treatment at a Boston area hospital. Suspecting COVID-19 was the cause of the illness, the executive requested a test, but was told by hospital staff that it was not necessary.<ref name=\"Arsenault\"/><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.wbur.org/commonhealth/2020/03/12/coronavirus-outbreak-biogen-conference-superspreading | title = Single Conference Linked To Most Mass. Coronavirus Cases Looks Like A 'Superspreading Event' | date= March 12, 2020 | first= Carey | last = Goldberg |website = [[WBUR-FM]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nbcboston.com/news/coronavirus/boston-biogen-meeting-coronavirus-warning/2089438/ |date= March 11, 2020 | first= Philip |last= Marcelo |first2=Matt |last2=O'Brien| publisher = NBC Boston | title = Biogen Meeting Tied to Coronavirus Cases Serves as Warning}}</ref>\n\n=== March ===\n[[File:Playground closed sign.jpg|thumb|upright|A closed playground after Mayor [[Marty Walsh (politician)|Marty Walsh]] announced the closure of all playgrounds until further notice.]]\n\nOn March 6, the BPHC announced 3 new presumptive cases of SARS-CoV-2.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/> Governor [[Charlie Baker]] declared a state of emergency for the state of Massachusetts on March 10.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/> Boston announced the closure of the Eliot K-8 school on March 11.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/> On March 13, the Boston Marathon was postponed to September 14, 2020.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/> Boston Mayor [[Marty Walsh (politician)|Marty Walsh]] announced the closure of all Boston schools.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/>\n\nOn March 15, Mayor Walsh declared a public health emergency due to the concerns over COVID-19. Restaurants, bar rooms, and nightclubs were required to reduce their capacity by at least 50 percent.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/> Governor [[Charlie Baker]] limited gatherings to below 25 people.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/> On March 16, Mayor Walsh announced the closure of the Boston Public Library system. The [[MBTA]] also announced that service would be reduced starting March 17. Mayor Walsh also announced the closure of all construction sites starting March 17.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/> On March 18, the City of Boston closed all playgrounds.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/>\n\nOn March 19, the Boston Water and Sewer Commission suspended all water service terminations.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/> On March 23, Massachusetts Governor Charlie Baker issued an order for all employers that do not provide essential services to close their workspaces. The limit of gatherings was lowered to 10 people. Massachusetts Department of Public Health issued a two-week stay-at-home advisory.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/> On March 25, Governor Baker extended the closure of schools to May 4.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/>\n\nOn March 30, Mayor Walsh announced that a partnership will create subsidized housing for 1,000 Boston Public Schools families at risk of displacement.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/> On March 31, Governor Baker extended his non-essential business closure to May 4.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/>\n\n=== April ===\nOn April 5, Mayor Walsh announced new regulations for social distancing in Boston. He encouraged everyone to wear a face covering when outside. The BPHC ordered for everyone except essential workers stay at home from 9 pm to 6 am everyday, enforcing a curfew. City Hall was closed to the public except for Tuesdays and Fridays, from 9 am to 5 pm. Every individual entering City Hall, including employees, was required to complete a self-screening for COVID-19 symptoms.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/>\n\nOn April 9, a new mortgage relief partnership was created to aid homeowners during the pandemic.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/> On April 16, Mayor Walsh announced that 1,000 residents will be invited to a Massachusetts study through antibody testing.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/> On April 19, Boston deployed seven Boston Public Works trucks to broadcast a message about COVID-19.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/>\n\nOn April 21, Governor Baker announced the closure of all K-12 schools in Massachusetts through the end of the school year.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/> On April 27, Boston Public Health Commission extended the public health emergency declaration until further notice.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/> On April 28, Governor Baker extended the stay-at-home advisory and non-essential business closure to May 18.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/> On April 29, the Public Health Advisory enforcing a curfew in Boston was extended to May 18.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/>\n\n=== May ===\n\nOn May 1, Massachusetts Governor Charlie Baker ordered all residents to wear a mask in public places when social distancing measures are not possible. This order goes into effect on May 6.<ref name=\"Boston-COVID-Timeline\"/>\n\n== Epidemiology ==\n=== Total cases and deaths ===\n{{As of|2020|05|03|alt=As of May 3}}, Boston had 9,929 confirmed reported cases of COVID-19.<ref name=\"Boston-Dashboard\"/> Deaths in Boston have been concentrated in the elderly. {{As of|2020|05|03|alt=As of May 3}}, Boston had 426 reported deaths due to SARS-CoV-2.<ref name=\"Boston-Dashboard\"/>\n\n=== Cases by category ===\nThe Boston Public Health Commission has rolled out a data dashboard for COVID-19 which is updated daily through Boston's government website.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable mw-datatable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right; font-size: 0.9em\"\n! colspan=\"11\" | Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) cases in Boston<ref name=\"Boston-Dashboard\"/>\n|-\n! \n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"3\" style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\"| Cases\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"3\" style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\"| Deaths\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"3\" style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\"| Recoveries\n! style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\"|\n|-\n! style=\"border-right: 2px solid #888;\" class=\"unsortable\"| Date\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Total Confirmed\n! Increase\n! % Change\n! style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" class=\"unsortable\" | Total Died\n! Increase\n! % Change\n! style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" class=\"unsortable\" | Total Recovered\n! Increase\n! % Change\n! style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" class=\"unsortable\" | Source\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | February 1 || style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" | 1 || 1 ||  || style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |  ||  ||  || style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |  ||  ||  || style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" | <ref name=\"Boston-Dashboard\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | \u22ee || style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" | 1 || 0 || 0% || style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |  ||  ||  || style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |  ||  ||  || style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" | <ref name=\"Boston-Dashboard\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | March 6 || style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" | 4 || 3 || +300% || style=\"border-left: 2px solid #888;\" |  ||  ||  |